## Part 6: Visual & Brand Identity Principles

### Color & Design Language

Your current site uses a dark theme with green (#10b981) accents — the "security terminal" aesthetic. This works well for the developer audience. Keep it.

**Rules:**
- Dark backgrounds signal "infrastructure" and "security" — not consumer SaaS
- Green accents = "safe / approved / operational"
- Red accents = "blocked / denied / alert" — use sparingly for threat scenarios
- Code blocks are your primary visual element — not stock photos, not illustrations
- Dashboard screenshots > marketing illustrations. Show the actual product.

### Logo & Name

"SUPRAWALL" — the name itself communicates "wall above." It works. Don't change it.

Use the shield iconography consistently. A shield = protection = security. It's the right symbol.

### Photography & Imagery

- Never use stock photos of people at computers
- Never use generic "AI" imagery (brains, robots, neural networks)
- DO use: terminal screenshots, dashboard screenshots, architecture diagrams, code snippets, attack/defense comparisons (like the Vault page's side-by-side)
- The split-screen "Insecure vs Secured" format on your Vault page is excellent. Use this pattern for every feature.

